{
"knowledge": "In scaled language‑model pretraining, training is typically stable when the product of batch size and the square root of the number of parameters (√P) remains roughly constant (≈10⁶). For N=214.66 M parameters, a batch size of ~500–700 keeps √(P)×bs≈10⁶, while very small batches amplify gradient variance and very large batches reduce effective learning‑rate for the optimizer. Learning rates in the 2.4×10⁻⁴–5.5×10⁻³ range are common; a rate >10⁻² often leads to unstable updates on this parameter scale.",
"expected_structure": "Loss will trade‑off: low lr combined with any bs may converge but to a high‑grad norm (high variance, risk of under‑fitting). High lr with large bs may cause exploding gradients or divergence. Ideal point likely near moderate‑lr (~4.9×10⁻⁴) and moderate‑bs (512–736), yielding balanced gradient variance and stable accumulation as in known scaling curves.",
"approach": "Treat (lr,bs) as two knobs of an inner product with a scaling target; first fix bs, find lr that yields √P·bs≈√(N)≈1.498×10⁵; then vary bs around that to see loss. Use a monotonic search: for each bs compute optimal lr using known scaling relationship, then run a quick loss‑estimate (e.g., cross‑entropy) to identify minimal.",
"uncertainties": ["Exact optimum may shift if loss surface is not monotonic due to data distribution; also small experimental noise could misrank combos, and training stability with bs=32 or 2048 might be unknown."]
}

{
  "knowledge": "In scaled language‑model pretraining with N≈2.1466e8 parameters, keeping the product √P·bs≈√N maintains stable gradient accumulation; learning rates above ~1e-2 often cause exploding updates, and very small batches increase variance. A reasonable search lies where √P·bs is constant (≈1.498e5) and lr is 2.4e-4 to 5.5e-3.",
  "expected_structure": "Loss will generally decrease as gradient variance is balanced; very low lr with any bs will converge slowly with high variance; very high lr with large bs will diverge; minimal loss expected near moderate lr (~4.9e-4) and moderate bs (~512–736).",
  "approach": "We will treat lr and bs jointly: for each bs we compute optimal lr using the √P·bs≈√N relationship, then evaluate the validation loss; this respects the interaction of lr and bs rather than treating them independently.",
  "uncertainties": ["We are uncertain about how stable training is at extreme jqbs 32 or 2048, and whether the √P·bs scaling holds if the loss surface is non‑monotonic."]
}

{
  "knowledge": "In scaled language‑model pretraining with N≈2.1466e8 parameters, keeping √P·bs≈√N maintains stable gradient accumulation; learning rates above ~1e-2 cause exploding updates, very small batches increase variance, and lr and bs interact so a simple scaling relation does not uniquely determine the optimal combination.",
  "expected_structure": "Loss decreases when gradient variance is balanced; very low lr or large bs increases variance, while very high lr with modest bs may cause divergence. Loss should be lowest near moderate lr (~4.9e-4) and moderate bs (~512–736) where both effects are mitigated.",
  "approach": "We will evaluate each independent (lr, bs) pair, computing the validation loss for each combination without assuming any closed‑form relation between lr and bs, thereby empirically determining which pairing minimizes loss.",
  "uncertainties": [
    "We are uncertain whether the √P·bs≈√N scaling remains valid if the loss surface is non‑monotonic or if the optimum differs from the rule of thumb.",
    "We are uncertain whether validation loss at extreme batch sizes (32 or 2048) is stable enough to represent true gradient behavior."
  ]
}

